⁵ Audacia, laryitio, avaritia] In such sentences as this, the poste- rior words do not always refer, or are not always opposed to the pre- ceding oneS, according to the order of their position. For here audacia is opposed to pudor, laryitio to virtus, and avaritia to abstinentia. Chap. xiv. Quos manus atque lingua, perjurio aut sanguine civili alc- δατ. Where perjurio refers to lingua, and sanquine to manus. Cic· copiis, tunicis, frumentoque suppeditato, exercitus, nostros vestivit, aluit, armant—M.

⁶ Ac me, cum ab reliquorum malis, &c.] Mutet. in his Var. Lect. lib. 16, c. 16, would read the sentence thus z—Ac me, cum ab reliquis malis moribus dissentirem, nihilominus honoris cupido eadem quae cae- teros, famaeque acidia vexabat. Ut, he sayS, honoris cupidinem, et ovidium samoe dixerit φιλας-[μιαν καὶ φιλοδοξίαν. Avidium autem, pro aviditate, dixisse Sallustium nemo mirabitur, qui eum jam tum, ut im- modicum antiquarum, et insolentium vocum affectatorem notatum esse meminit. Jam vero ut aperfido perfidiam, ab invido invidiam, sic ab avido ovidium dici, analogia quidem facile patitur. This is an in- genious emendation ; I wish it were supported by any MSS. The read- ings are various in different editions : some read cupidum, i. e., vexabat me cupidum honoris, which would remove all difficulty if supported by any good MSS. Me, in the text, is governed by vexabat, understood. It very often happens that a verb in the latter clause of a sentence is understood, or must be taken in another clause, as here, and Virg.
